BOOK XVI

A RIDDLE1 OF THE NUMBER THREE

AUSons To SYMMACHUS

HIDING away amongst my trash was a wretched little book3 and I would to Heaven it had kept hidden and were not coming to grief by betraying itself as the shrew-mouse did.·2 When, like Euclio's cock,3 I had disinterred this from a litter of crumbling paper and had shaken out the dust, I read it again, and, as a grasping usurer, preferred to put a bad coin out to interest rather than keep it by me. Then, while reflecting, not in those words of Catullus,
